05134nam a22007335i 9780226483078DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2017    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802264830787 a10.7208/97802264830782doi  a(DE-B1597)521373  a(OCoLC)1001928153  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aJC179.M753bS95 2018 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a321.90942231 aSullivan, Vickie B., eauthor.10aMontesquieu and the Despotic Ideas of Europe :bAn Interpretation of "The Spirit of the Laws" /cVickie B. Sullivan. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note on Citations -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. The Ideas of Montesquieu's Modern European Predecessors -- t1. The Greatness of Machiavelli and the Despotic Disease of His Politics- Both Princely and Republican -- t2. Montesquieu's Attack on the Political Errors of Hobbes -- tPart II. Christian Ideas -- t3. Religious Ideas and the Force of Christian Ones in Modern Europe -- t4. The Ideas of Early Christianity, Their Absorption in Roman Law, and Their Abusive Reverberations in Modern Europe -- tPart III. The Ideas of the Ancient Legislators -- t5. Montesquieu's Opposition to Plato's Belles Idées and Their Diffusion -- t6. Aristotle's "Manner of Thinking" and the Deleterious Use of His Ideas -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMontesquieu is rightly famous as a tireless critic of despotism, which he associates in his writings overtly with Asia and the Middle East and not with the apparently more moderate Western models of governance found throughout Europe. However, a careful reading of Montesquieu reveals that he recognizes a susceptibility to despotic practices in the West-and that the threat emanates not from the East, but from certain despotic ideas that inform such Western institutions as the French monarchy and the Roman Catholic Church.             Nowhere is Montesquieu's critique of the despotic ideas of Europe more powerful than in his enormously influential The Spirit of the Laws, and Vickie B. Sullivan guides readers through Montesquieu's sometimes veiled, yet sharply critical accounts of Machiavelli, Hobbes, Aristotle, and Plato, as well as various Christian thinkers. He finds deleterious consequences, for example, in brutal Machiavellianism, in Hobbes's justifications for the rule of one, in Plato's reasoning that denied slaves the right of natural defense, and in the Christian teachings that equated heresy with treason and informed the Inquisition. In this new reading of Montesquieu's masterwork, Sullivan corrects the misconception that it offers simple, objective observations, showing it instead to be a powerful critique of European politics that would become remarkably and regrettably prescient after Montesquieu's death when despotism wound its way through Europe.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aChristianity and politicszEurope. 0aDespotismxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aDespotismzEurope. 0aMachiavelli, Niccolao. 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 4aAristotle. 4aChristian doctrines. 4aHobbes. 4aMachiavelli. 4aMontesquieu. 4aPlato. 4aSparta. 4acriminal justice. 4adespotism. 4aphilosopher as legislator. 4aslavery. 70(DE-601)1048141280(DE-588)4076226-9aPolitische Philosophie2gnd 70(DE-601)1051305910(DE-588)4206090-4aAutokratie2gnd 70(DE-601)1055574630(DE-588)4149920-7aDiktatur2gnd 70(DE-601)10556303X0(DE-588)4149206-7aDespotie2gnd 70(DE-601)1061016840(DE-588)4070000-8aChristliche Politik2gnd 70(DE-601)1064017500(DE-